The paper presents an algorithm that combines natural language processing and fast robot motion planning, which suggests that it could belong to the Robotics (cs.RO) sub-category. The use of natural language processing also suggests that it could belong to the Natural Language Processing (cs.CL) sub-category. The paper also mentions the use of optimization-based motion planning, which could place it in the Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category. The use of factor graphs and conditional random fields for learning coefficients suggests that it could belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category. Finally, the mention of dynamic scenes and orientation specification suggests that it could belong to the Computer Vision (cs.CV) sub-category.
